Xegony</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ujerit.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jerit</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/7/01 9:42:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Here's the REAL Top 100 Reasons Why DAoC is better than </span><hr size=1> Xenix,<br>
<br>
The rules are actually fairly lax from what I've seen. The things that seem to get most folks in trouble are what a reasonable person (at least in my opinion) would consider fairly obvious.<br>
<br>
Call your character 'Imdarthvader' or 'Noobiboy' and someone will most likely petition you. Go around talking dood speak and most likely someone will petition you over it.<br>
<br>
Behaving like a complete moron, attempting to leech off of others or just in general attempting to cause grief to others in some form or fashion will get folks down on your case.<br>
<br>
I've heard people asking in game technical questions and get prompt courteous responses that are in no way 'in character'. Never heard anyone give anyone any grief over reasonable requests, such as how do I do 'x' or could someone point me in the direction of NPC 'y' or in what direction does city 'z' lie?<br>
<br>
A few people speak in 'Thees' and 'Thous', but most of the RPers that I run across tend to take on more of a 'character' persona. An irritable Irishman with a brogue(sp?) accent kind of thing.<br>
<br>
The majority of the people I have run across have just been friendly people who wish to immerse themselves in the game without dealing with folks who jar you out of the immersion factor (at least this is my percepetion from playing on the Guinevere RP server).<br>
<br>
Hope this answers your question. <p>Jerit  Albion Mercenary<BR>
Keister Albion Theurgist</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=camthorntikwanleep>Camthorn TiKwanLeep</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/9/01 11:00:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well......</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> DAoC gives you more for the time you invest than EQ.<br>
<br>
That's a huge attraction to all but the more masochistic gamers... you know, the ones who play Diablo2 in Nightmare mode (char wipe on death), and played the original Wizardry for months on end... <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, but according to the Agents in The Matrix, &quot;Human beings define themselves by suffering.&quot;   Early versions of the Matrix were paradises, and they were rejected en masse.  It's only when struggling, fighting against impossible odds that humans feel fulfilled.   It doesn't matter that they never experience the rewards of this struggle, the fight is the defining factor in a human's life.<br>
<br>
So.  DAoC which gives you more of a paradise, and more gain for less pain...<br>
<br>
Or EQ which gives you so much pain that any measurable gain evokes an almost orgasmic response in the player.<br>
<br>
All other things being equal(ease of play, availability, friendship/loyalty factors, cost, etc) according to the philosophy of the Matrix, humans will choose EQ.<br>
<br>
DAoC doesn't run on my OS(well, not officially at least and I don't feel like messing with it) but I'll probably try it when it does.  I figure the lifespan of the MMORPG is limited, just like the old MUDs and MOOs, so I better get every ounce of enjoyment out of one that I can.  If the high-level game is more fun than the low-level(and if it's not I'll shoot someone. It's been only a little more fun than pulling teeth so far in the gameplay aspects. The only fun thing is the social interaction in a fantasy setting) then why not get to the high-level ASAP?<br>
<br>
Sooner or later Everquest will go away. The next big thing will come out and it won't be profitable/possible to sustain the EQ servers/staff.  Maybe other games will steal the playerbase, maybe, maybe, maybe.  The exact reason is not important, I feel comfortable saying EQ has a limited lifespan.  So why not play a game where you can accomplish something meaningful in the short(relatively speaking) time that you spend playing it that you can look back on with pride after you can no longer play? <br>
<br>
Steven <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ujinpo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jinpo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 275<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/9/01 12:05:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well......</span><hr size=1> Here's my take on it:<br>
<br>
The wife says: I'll be back in 2 hours.<br>
<br>
Hmmmmm...which game do I play?<br>
<br>
If I choose EQ:<br>
10min: log in, check stuff/bank supply run, get ready to play<br>
15min: guild chat, which is a joy being in my guild - they are just great people <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
20min: travel to appropriate zone to level in<br>
15min: look for a bind<br>
20min: look for a group<br>
25min: play<br>
5min: &quot;time to split&quot; talk, with mandatory &quot;last pull&quot;<br>
5min: find safe camp spot/run to bank to cash PHAT LEWTZ<br>
5min: settle in, camp<br>
<br>
If I choose DaoC:<br>
5min: log in, check stuff<br>
5min: guild chat/get quest/task<br>
5min: travel to appropriate zone to level in<br>
95min: play<br>
5min: sell/clean up/log out<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong...I love EQ--but the way my RL is right now I just don't have the time to spend 4-6 hours on it nowadays. DaoC is nice when I'm short on time...<br>
<br>
Anything less than 1 hour - Diablo 2<br>
Anything more than 4 hours - EQ <p><html><body>
